text:
When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered. The people who took the drug are immortal, but also are monsters. 

The drug wreaked havoc on their ability to feel positive things, or care for other people.  You had lived your life resenting your younger brothers and sisters, and the researchers, but now you feel guilty.

You decide to go on a road trip to find your family who took the drug, to apologize for your resentment. You find your family, but they are not the same. They are cold, and distant. They don't care about you, and they don't care about each other. 

You decide to stay with them, and try to help them. You try to show them that they can still feel love, and that they can still care about each other. You try to teach them how to be human again. 

You are the only one who can help them. You are the only one who can teach them how to be human again. You are the only one who can save them. You are the only one who can save yourself.  Nobody else cares about them enough, and they don't care about anyone else. Your siblings are cold and uncaring immortals, going through life with no meaning. They are sociopathic monsters, not caring who they hurt, and have lost all connection with other humans. 


After trying to help them, and getting nowhere, you come to the conclusion that there is nothing that can be done for them. 
You may be the "Lost Generation", but it is they who are truly lost .  You erect a tomb for them, at the family plot. You symbolically bury them with the note that you wrote to them, and leave to live the rest of your life.
